{
  "title": "Deep Dive: zipapp Standard Library Module in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This explainer provides a comprehensive overview of the zipapp module, a significant addition to the Python 3.12 standard library that simplifies packaging multiple Python applications within a single executable.",

  "key_points": [
    "The zipapp module enables the creation of standalone executables from Python scripts and their dependencies.",
    "It offers increased portability, as the executable does not require Python to be installed on the target system.",
    "zipapp consolidates the script and its dependencies (imported modules) into a single file with a .pyz extension.",
    "The generated executable can be run on any platform that has a Python interpreter compatible with the version used during package creation.",
    "In Python 3.12, zipapp offers improved support for multi-threading and better handling of system libraries.",
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "Python",
      "code": "import zipapp\n\nscript = 'my_script.py'\napp = zipapp.App(script, base='.', format=zipapp.ZIP_APP)\napp.run()"
    },
    {
      "language": "Python",
      "code": "import os\n# my_script.py contains 'os.system("ls")' to list the current directory.\nimport zipapp\napp = zipapp.App('my_script.py', base='.', format=zipapp.ZIP_APP)\napp.run()"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "Introduced in Python 3.12",
    "Improved support for multi-threading and system libraries handling compared to previous versions",
    "Compatible with any platform that has a compatible Python interpreter"
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "Not all Python modules can be included in the generated executable due to platform-specific dependencies or C extensions.",
    "When using third-party libraries, ensure they are compatible with the zipapp module and Python version.",
    "The zipapp executable may take longer to run compared to a regular script, as it first needs to unpack the .pyz file."
  ]
